{
  "texts": [
    "Even if the value is recorded in the data set, it may not be exactly same as the true value which is known as measurement error.",
    "This section will describe these two main types of noise in observed data and introduce algorithms that aim to handle these forms of noise in structure learning with discrete or continuous variables.",
    "Missing data is a common and serious problem in many real-world scientific research areas such as medical research and gene analysis.",
    "Rubin (1976) categorised missing data into three types: Missing Completely At Random (MCAR), Missing At Random (MAR) and Missing Not At Random (MNAR).",
    "In the MCAR case, the missingness of data is a purely random process and is not dependent on any other substantive variables."
  ]
}